examples.en: Right now, could you calculate the number of people who came today?
examples.ja: 今日の入場人数を今すぐ算定してもらってもいいですか？

examples.en: My mother is good at calculating the money going in and out of the house every month.
examples.ja: 母は毎月の家のお金の出入りを算定することが上手です。

examples.en: We calculated the sales of shaved ice and balloons from the fireworks display.
examples.ja: 花火大会の時のかき氷と風船の売り上げを算定しました。

meaning_mnemonic:
When you <kanji>calculate</kanji> and <kanji>determine</kanji> (the calculation), you are determining the calculation. That's why this word is <vocabulary>to calculate</vocabulary>.

Unlike 計算する, which means “to calculate” in general, 算定する is a formal word that focuses more on the final value of a calculation, instead of the process of calculating itself.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word, which usually means on'yomi readings from the kanji. If you know the readings of your kanji you'll know how to read this as well.

examples.en: Do you know the phone number of the prime minister's office?
examples.ja: 総理府の電話番号を知っていますか？

examples.en: The Deputy Director General of the Prime Minister's Office was looking for you.
examples.ja: 総理府次長がお前のことをさがしていたぞ。

examples.en: I knew nothing about her except that she worked in the prime minister’s office.
examples.ja: 彼女のことについては、総理府で働いているという以外には何も知らなかった。

meaning_mnemonic:
The prime minister's (総理) <kanji>government</kanji> is where he does all his governmenting. It's where the Japanese <vocabulary>Prime Minister's Office</vocabulary> (aka the <vocabulary>Cabinet Office</vocabulary>) is located as well.

総理府 was actually renamed 内閣府 in 2001, so you'd generally only use 総理府 to talk about the Cabinet Offices from back in the day.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word, which usually means on'yomi readings from the kanji. If you know the readings of your kanji you'll know how to read this as well. It will help to know 総理 beforehand as well.

examples.en: I have a lot of experience in exploring the desert.
examples.ja: 私は砂漠探索の経験が豊富です。

meaning_mnemonic: A <kanji>sand</kanji> <kanji>desert</kanji> is just a <vocabulary>desert</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: While I was looking at the flow of the river I had a vague feeling of anxiety.
examples.ja: 漠然とした不安を感じながら、私は川の流れを見詰めていました。

meaning_mnemonic:
Something with a <kanji>vague</kanji> <kanji>nature</kanji> is also quite <vocabulary>vague</vocabulary>. 

Note that you need to add と to the end of this word to make it an adverb, and たる to make it an adjective!
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: Aren’t I too young to be called a middle-aged woman? I’m hurt.
examples.ja: おばちゃんって呼ばれる年齢かなあ。傷つくなあ。

meaning_mnemonic: Remember how 傷 is "wound"? Now a wound is つくing to you, or in other words, is getting attached to you. If you get a wound attached to your body, you are probably going <vocabulary>to get hurt</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: The reading is the same as the word 傷.

examples.en: Our oldest son does nothing but play baseball. He doesn’t have a girlfriend either.
examples.ja: うちの長男は野球一筋なのよ。女っ気も無くてさ。

meaning_mnemonic: You have <kanji>one</kanji> <kanji>muscle</kanji>, therefore it only does one thing. That's it. It is <vocabulary>single mindedly</vocabulary> doing that one thing. It is <vocabulary>intently</vocabulary> and <vocabulary>earnestly</vocabulary> doing that one thing.
reading_mnemonic: The reading is a bit weird. It's the kun'yomi readings, where 一 is ひと and 筋 is すじ. Look back on the vocab words that use these readings to remember this one.

examples.en: It seems that the lid wasn't properly closed, so there's sauce leaking from one side.
examples.ja: フタがちゃんと閉まっていなかったみたいで、横からソースが垂れている。

examples.en: Something was wrong with the faucet last night, and the sound of dripping water bothered me so much I hardly got any sleep.
examples.ja: 昨夜ジャグチの調子が悪くて、水がポタポタ垂れる音が気になってほとんど寝られなかった。

examples.en: Although Jazz's tail had been drooping the entire time Jiro was out, the moment he heard his car, it sprang straight up and started wagging furiously.
examples.ja: ジャズの尻尾は次郎がいない間ずっと垂れ下がっていたが、彼の車が聞こえた途端、ぴんとはね上がり、激しく振り始めた。

meaning_mnemonic:
If 垂らす is "to dangle something" then 垂れる is <vocabulary>to dangle</vocabulary> or <vocabulary>to drip</vocabulary> on its own. So you can use 垂れる to describe your dog's floppy ears hanging down or your ice cream’s melty goodness dripping away. You know this because it's <reading>rare</reading> (れる) to witness the moment something starts dangling or dripping down.

Sometimes, 垂れる can also take a direct object in specific expressions, like 説教を垂れる (to give a preachy lecture), こうべを垂れる (to bow one's head in humility), or the crude slang クソを垂れる (to drop a load).
reading_mnemonic: The reading is the same as 垂らす.

examples.en: Don’t you think that the Japanese government should have declared a state of emergency at the time?
examples.ja: あの時、日本政府は非常事態を宣言するべきだったと思わないかい。

meaning_mnemonic: If 宣言 is a "proclamation," then the verb version will be <vocabulary>to proclaim</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: My buddy is ridiculously interesting and he’s great at livening up parties.
examples.ja: 俺の友達はメチャクチャ面白くて、パーティーを盛り上げるのが得意なんだよ。

meaning_mnemonic: 盛る is "to heap up." If you "raise" (上げる) what you heap up, well, that comes with heaping something up, making this word <vocabulary>to heap up</vocabulary> or <vocabulary>to pile up</vocabulary>. This word is also used when you want <vocabulary>to liven up</vocabulary> some things. Heap up that energy and stir things up!
reading_mnemonic: The reading comes from 盛る and 上げる. Know those words and you'll be able to read this one too.

examples.en: He is not a traitor. He’s just naturally a little slow.
examples.ja: 彼は裏切り者なんかじゃないよ。ただ、生まれつきちょっととぼけているだけさ。

examples.en: They use this facility to kill traitors.
examples.ja: 奴らは裏切り者を殺すのにこの施設を利用している。

meaning_mnemonic: <kanji>Someone</kanji> who backstabs (裏切り) someone is a <vocabulary>traitor</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: The reading is 裏切り and an exception reading for 者. Just think about how you'd think of a traitor as a "thing" (物) and not a person.

examples.en: We decided to temporarily close our shop for a bunch of reasons.
examples.ja: 諸々の理由がありまして、しばらく一時的に店を閉めることにしました。

meaning_mnemonic: You have <kanji>various</kanji> <kanji>various</kanji> things. They are <vocabulary>various</vocabulary>. You have <vocabulary>all kinds of</vocabulary> them.
reading_mnemonic: The reading is a bit weird. Just think about how when you have various things, you probably have a lot of things. What do you want? You want <reading>more</reading> (もろ) of those things. <reading>More more</reading> more!

examples.en: Oh come on, it was so obvious! There was no chemistry between you two! You definitely shouldn’t call that girl with the braided hair!
examples.ja: おいおい、頼むよ。明らかにお前たちの相性全然よくなかっただろ！絶対にあの三つ編みの女に電話なんてしない方がいいって！

meaning_mnemonic: 編む is "to knit." When you knit in <kanji>three</kanji>s, you are knitting in a braid style. What do you braid? Hair. That makes this <vocabulary>braided hair</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: The reading is the み from 三つ and つ and 編む combined into one (or should I say three?) braids. Just watch out because this isn't みっつあみ, it's just みつあみ. Listen to the audio a few times to make sure you remember how it's spelled and pronounced!

examples.en: I don't think they will be satisfied with just money.
examples.ja: 金を払うだけで、彼らが納まるとは思えないけどな。

meaning_mnemonic:
If 納める is "to supply" or "to deliver," then this word is when things have been delivered: so it's <vocabulary>to settle into</vocabulary> or <vocabulary>to be satisfied</vocabulary>. 

納まる means something or someone has found its right place and settled there. It often implies that there was a prior state of uncertainty or dissatisfaction, but now everything is in its right place.

Like most verbs with まる as okurigana, this is an intransitive verb. That means it happens by itself, with no emphasis on the person or thing that's making something settle or be satisfied.
reading_mnemonic: The reading is the same as 納める.

examples.en: I'm convinced by his opinion.
examples.ja: 彼の意見には納得だね。

examples.en: That I can't understand!
examples.ja: それは納得できない！

examples.en: You made my daughter consent using money, didn’t you?
examples.ja: どうせお前は娘を金ずくで納得させたんだろう？

meaning_mnemonic: I will <kanji>supply</kanji> and you will <kanji>acquire</kanji>. Does that sound good? Do I have your <vocabulary>consent</vocabulary>? I can see that you're <vocabulary>understanding</vocabulary> and <vocabulary>being convinced</vocabulary>. You're planning on <vocabulary>accepting</vocabulary> my proposition, aren't you?
reading_mnemonic: The reading is a bit weird for 納. Just imagine asking the consent question from the meaning, then have the other person say "<reading>Nahh!</reading> (なっ), no consent!"

examples.en: Can you change this sentence into a negative sentence?
examples.ja: この文章を否定形にすることができますか。

meaning_mnemonic: 否定 is denial. Remember how 形 sometimes refers to grammar tense / type? Well, with a denial type grammar, you have a <vocabulary>negative form</vocabulary>, making it a <vocabulary>negative sentence</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: I deny the theory that natto goes well with rice.
examples.ja: 私は納豆がご飯に合うって説は否定しますね。

meaning_mnemonic: If 否定 is "denial," then the verb version would be <vocabulary>to deny</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own. Will help to know the word 否定 as well.

examples.en: Do you have anyone you respect?
examples.ja: 尊敬する人はいますか？

meaning_mnemonic: If 尊敬 is "respect" then the verb version would be <vocabulary>to respect</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: I often mix up honorific Japanese with humble Japanese.
examples.ja: よく尊敬語と謙譲語がゴチャゴチャになってしまいます。

meaning_mnemonic: 尊敬 is respect. A respect <kanji>language</kanji> is <vocabulary>honorific Japanese</vocabulary> (or <vocabulary>honorific language</vocabulary>, though usually this refers to Japanese).
reading_mnemonic: The reading is 尊敬 plus 語 put together.

examples.en: Technology has greatly changed people's lives.
examples.ja: テクノロジーは人々の暮らしを大きく変えました。

examples.en: I'm trying not to forget to be grateful for everyday life.
examples.ja: 日々の暮らしに感謝することを忘れないようにしています。

examples.en: Rural life is boring. Then again, city life might be convenient, but it comes with a lot of stress too, right?
examples.ja: 田舎暮らしは退屈だよ。でもさ、都会での暮らしは便利だけど、ストレスも多いよね？

meaning_mnemonic: If 暮らす is "to live" or "to live one's life" then the noun version would be simply <vocabulary>life</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: The reading is the same as 暮らす. However, 暮らし often gets stuck on the end of other nouns, like 田舎暮らし (country life), so watch out for rendaku when that happens.

examples.en: I was ashamed when I got zero on the homophone test.
examples.ja: 同音異義語のテストで０点を取って、恥をかいてしまいました。

examples.en: How many homophones are there in Japanese?
examples.ja: 日本語には、同音異義語はいくつありますか？

examples.en: I made a YouTube video about homonyms, so please take a look.
examples.ja: 同音異義語に関するユーチューブビデオを作ったので、よかったら見てみてください。

meaning_mnemonic: You have the <kanji>same</kanji> <kanji>sound</kanji> with a <vocabulary>different meaning</vocabulary> (異義), and it's a part of <kanji>language</kanji>. Same sounds... different meanings... that sounds like a <vocabulary>homophone</vocabulary>, or a <vocabulary>homonym</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own. All I know is there's probably not a homonym for this word, for it is huge.

examples.en: I don’t want you guys to use someone else’s work regardless of whether or not it is subject to copyright.
examples.ja: 著作権の対象となるかどうかに関わらず、他人の作品は使用しないでください。

meaning_mnemonic:
著作 is "writing" or "authorship." The <kanji>rights</kanji> that writing has is what's known as <vocabulary>copyright</vocabulary>.

Note that 著作権 refers to copyright for anything, not just writing.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own. Will help to know 著作 first, too.

examples.en: This summer is definitely more humid than it was last year.
examples.ja: 今年の夏は絶対去年よりも蒸し暑いよね。

meaning_mnemonic: If it’s a <kanji>steam</kanji>ing <kanji>hot</kanji> day, it means the weather is <vocabulary>hot and humid</vocabulary> (or you can just say <vocabulary>humid</vocabulary>, because that usually implies hotness too). This is a useful word for summers in Japan, since you'll complain about this all the time.
reading_mnemonic: The reading comes from 蒸れる and 暑い. Know those and you know this too.

examples.en: There you go again. Girls always bring up old issues. I don’t want to deal with that.
examples.ja: またかよ。女はすぐ昔の話を蒸し返すよな。やってられないわ。

meaning_mnemonic: You <kanji>steam</kanji> something to <kanji>return</kanji> it to its previously warm state. This is when you go <vocabulary>to reheat</vocabulary> something. But we usually use it to talk about bringing something up again and again in conversations or arguments. That's why it means <vocabulary>to rehash</vocabulary> or <vocabulary>to bring up again</vocabulary>. You're bringing up memories from the past and steaming them up again.
reading_mnemonic: The reading comes from 蒸れる and 返す. Combine this knowledge to reheat your memories.

examples.en: Although he didn’t get the promotion he had been expecting, he put on a good face and congratulated the people who did.
examples.ja: 予想していた昇進が無かったが、彼は平気を装って昇進した社員たちにおめでとうと言った。

meaning_mnemonic: If you go to <kanji>attire</kanji> yourself, you're covering up who you are and trying to be someone else. You are trying <vocabulary>to feign</vocabulary>. You are trying <vocabulary>to wear</vocabulary> a lie. You are trying <vocabulary>to pretend</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: While you go <vocabulary>to feign</vocabulary> that you're someone or something else, someone calls you out on it: "<reading>you so</reading> (よそお) much a liar!"

examples.en: If the flight is delayed, can I get some kind of compensation?
examples.ja: もし飛行機が遅れたら、補償金のようなものは支払われたりするんでしょうか。

meaning_mnemonic: If something or someone is <kanji>slow</kanji>, and they "do slow" they are going <vocabulary>to be late</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: What is slow and probably going to be late all the time? A big <reading>oak</reading> (おく). Oaks have trouble moving, and are slow, and therefore are always late, too.

examples.en: What is your reason for being late?
examples.ja: 遅刻の理由は何ですか？

examples.en: Uh-oh, I'm running late!
examples.ja: やばいっ、遅刻する！

examples.en: I was late three days in a row.
examples.ja: 三日連続で遅刻してしまいました。

examples.en: Hurry up, or you'll be late again! Being late is stealing time.
examples.ja: 早くしないと、また遅刻だよ！遅刻は時間泥棒なんだよ。

meaning_mnemonic: A <kanji>slow</kanji> <kanji>carve</kanji> is so slow. If you carve something slowly, it will take you a long time. You will <vocabulary>be late</vocabulary> with a slow carve like that.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: The bus was delayed for a long time and I was late to the meeting.
examples.ja: バスの大幅な遅延により会議に遅れてしまった。

meaning_mnemonic: I was too <kanji>slow</kanji>, so we'll have to <kanji>prolong</kanji> the time in which this product will come out. This is a <vocabulary>delay</vocabulary> :(
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: I dropped the sculpture and it broke in half.
examples.ja: 彫刻を落として、真っ二つに割ってしまいました。

meaning_mnemonic: You <kanji>carve</kanji> then you <kanji>carve</kanji> again. So much carving until, wait, wow, it looks like something! All that carving became a <vocabulary>sculpture</vocabulary>!
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: The nurse is good at measuring people’s blood pressure.
examples.ja: その看護師さんは、血圧を測るのが上手です。

meaning_mnemonic: Because the hiragana ends with an う sound, you know this word is a verb. The kanji itself means <kanji>measure</kanji> so the verb vocab means <vocabulary>to measure</vocabulary>. This word generally has to do with scientific or medical measurements.
reading_mnemonic: Remember another word that means "to measure?" It is 量る, and has the same reading as this word. That should make things easier to remember.

examples.en: My guess is that he won the lottery and has moved to the Bahamas.
examples.ja: 私の推測では、彼は宝くじが当たって、バハマに引っ越しています。

examples.en: I imagine that you are all probably making similar inferences to a greater or lesser extent.
examples.ja: おそらく皆さんも、大なり小なり似たような推測をされていると思います。

examples.en: How do you think Japan will change in the future? Please feel free to include speculation in your answer.
examples.ja: あなたは日本は今後どうなるとお考えでしょうか。推測を交えてで結構ですので、お答えください。

meaning_mnemonic:
When you <kanji>infer</kanji> and <kanji>measure</kanji>, it’ll lead to some sort of <vocabulary>conjecture</vocabulary>, <vocabulary>speculation</vocabulary>, or <vocabulary>guess</vocabulary> about something.

推測 means guessing based on known facts or information, while using reasoning to fill in the gaps.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: Scientists failed to predict the massive earthquake.
examples.ja: 科学者たちは、大地震の予測に失敗した。

examples.en: As we have written in numerous blog posts, we have been predicting this for some time.
examples.ja: 何度もブログ記事で書いた通り、私たちはこの事を以前から予測していました。

examples.en: The accurate prediction of stock prices is impossible. If that were possible, these guys would be managing assets themselves, instead of working in sales.
examples.ja: 株価の正確な未来予測は不可能です。そんなことができるなら、彼らはセールスではなく自分で資産運用をしているはずです。

meaning_mnemonic: A beforehand measure is when you make a prediction or estimation about something. While 予想 often refers to a subjective prediction, 予測 generally refers to forecasting future events based on objective evidence.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: How can I become a member of Antarctic exploration party?
examples.ja: 南極観測隊のメンバーになるにはどうすればいいですか。

meaning_mnemonic: <kanji>View</kanji> and <kanji>measure</kanji> what you are watching. This is <vocabulary>observation</vocabulary>. It is no mere viewing, it is more than that.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: We took a video of our puppy tearing open Christmas presents.
examples.ja: うちのワンコがクリスマスプレゼントの包装をビリビリ破っているビデオを撮ったのよ。

meaning_mnemonic: Because the hiragana ends with an う sound, you know this word is a verb. The kanji itself means <kanji>tear</kanji> so the verb version is <vocabulary>to tear</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: You start <vocabulary>to tear</vocabulary> the cloth. You don't know if you're supposed to or not. The crowd isn't sure either. You hear kind of a <reading>yah boo</reading> (やぶ) reaction going on, making you unsure if you should continue or stop. Yah! Boo. Yah! Boo!

examples.en: The rabbit hutch was destroyed by the fire.
examples.ja: 兎小屋は火事によって破壊されました。

meaning_mnemonic: <kanji>Tear</kanji> and <kanji>break</kanji> everything, taking it all down. <vocabulary>Destruction</vocabulary>! <vocabulary>Demolition</vocabulary>!
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: The ship carrying the famous sword of the Edo period was shipwrecked in a storm.
examples.ja: 江戸時代の有名な刀を載せた船は、嵐によって破船してしまいました。

meaning_mnemonic: A <kanji>tear</kanji> in your <kanji>ship</kanji> will cause it to wreck, making it a <vocabulary>shipwreck</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: It’s rumored that his grandfather was a bankrupt farmer of the Edo period.
examples.ja: 彼の祖父は江戸時代の破産した百姓だという噂だ。

meaning_mnemonic: If someone <kanji>tear</kanji>s all your <kanji>property</kanji> it'll lead to <vocabulary>bankruptcy</vocabulary>. With all your property torn, you're going to <vocabulary>go bankrupt</vocabulary>. What mean person did that?
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: I saw a dying possum on a country road.
examples.ja: 田舎道で死にかけのフクロネズミを見ました。

meaning_mnemonic: A <kanji>rice paddy</kanji> and a <kanji>cottage</kanji>. This is the image of the <vocabulary>countryside</vocabulary> to me. This is <vocabulary>rural</vocabulary>. Just cottages and rice paddies...
reading_mnemonic: The reading doesn't really make sense for the kanji, and is an exception for sure. Just think about how when you're in the <vocabulary>countryside</vocabulary> you're <reading>in 中</reading> (いなか) of nowhere.

examples.en: The barracks were filled with such an offensive stench that I could barely breathe.
examples.ja: その兵舎には異臭が漂っており、息をするのもやっとだった。

meaning_mnemonic: A <kanji>soldier</kanji> <kanji>cottage</kanji> is a place where the soldiers stay. This is the <vocabulary>barracks</vocabulary>.
reading_mnemonic: This is a jukugo word that uses the on'yomi readings of the kanji. You should be able to read this on your own.

examples.en: I heard that the government office building was struck by lightning.
examples.ja: 庁舎に雷が落ちたみたいだよ。
